Sobolev H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} Geometry of the Symplectomorphism Group

J. Benn and A. Suri School of Engineering and Advanced Technology, Massey University,
Palmerston North, New Zealand. j.benn1@massey.ac.nz Department of Mathematics, Faculty of sciences
Bu-Ali Sina University, Hamedan 65178, Iran. ali.suri@gmail.com & a.suri@basu.ac.ir
Abstract.

For a closed symplectic manifold (M,ω)𝑀𝜔(M,\omega) with compatible Riemannian metric g𝑔g we study the Sobolev H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} geometry of the group of all Hssuperscript𝐻𝑠H^{s} diffeomorphisms on M𝑀M which preserve the symplectic structure. We show that, for sufficiently large s𝑠s, the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric admits globally defined geodesics and the corresponding exponential map is a non-linear Fredholm map of index zero. Finally, we show that the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric carries conjugate points via some simple examples.

Keywords: Symplectic manifold; Geodesic; Spray; Variation; Hilbert manifold; Fredholm operator; Sobolev metric; Conjugate point; Einstein manifold.

2010 Mathematical Subject Classification. 58D05, 53D35, 35Q35, 47H99, 53C99.

1. Introduction

A number of well-known nonlinear partial differential equations of mathematical physics arise as geodesic equations on various infinite dimensional Lie groups. The most fundamental example is the Euler equations of ideal hydrodynamics where Arnold [1] noticed that a curve η​(t)𝜂𝑡\eta(t) in the group of smooth volume preserving diffeomorphisms is a geodesic of the right-invariant L2superscript𝐿2L^{2} metric if and only if the velocity field v​(t)=η​(t)˙∘η−1​(t)𝑣𝑡˙𝜂𝑡superscript𝜂1𝑡v(t)=\dot{\eta(t)}\circ\eta^{-1}(t) solves the Euler equations of hydrodynamics. Subsequently, Ebin and Marsden [5] showed that the volume preserving diffeomorphism group can be given the structure of a Hilbert manifold and proved that the corresponding geodesic equation is actually a smooth ordinary differential equation, hence rigourously justifying the infinite dimensional geometric constructions. Since then, much research has focused on finding geometric formulations for other conservative systems in continuum mechanics. For examples of these see Arnold-Khesin [2], Marsden and Ratiu [13], Schmid [17], Taylor [19], Vizman [20], Zeitlin and Kambe [21], or Khesin-Wendt [10] and the references therein.

Two motivations for the present work are the Lagrangian-averaged Euler equations as considered by Shkoller [16] and the symplectic diffeomorphism group equipped with the L2superscript𝐿2L^{2} metric as considered by Ebin [4].

The Lagrangian-averaged Euler equations were first introduced by Holm, Marsden, and Ratiu in Euclidean space, and describe the mean hydrodynamic motion of an incompressible fluid. Shkoller [16] realized the Lagrangian-averaged Euler equations as the Euler-Poincare equations associated with the geodesic flow of the right-invariant Sobolev H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric on the group of volume-preserving diffeomorphisms of a compact n-dimensional Riemannian manifold. He showed that, for sufficiently large s𝑠s, the geodesic spray is continuously differentiable so that a standard Picard iteration argument proves existence and uniqueness of solutions on a finite time interval. Kouranbaeva and Oliver [11] have subsequently shown that when the underlying manifold is two dimensional the Lagrangian-averaged Euler equations admit weak global solutions.

In the present work we consider a closed symplectic manifold, with symplectic form ω𝜔\omega, and the group of Sobolev Hssuperscript𝐻𝑠H^{s} symplectic diffeomorphisms 𝒟ωs​(M)subscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔𝑀\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega}(M) of M𝑀M equipped with the right-invariant Sobolev H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric on vector fields. Our main theorem is

Theorem 1.1.

Let (M,ω)𝑀𝜔(M,\omega) be a closed, 2​n2𝑛2n-dimensional symplectic manifold with compatible Riemannian metric g𝑔g. Then, for s>n+3𝑠𝑛3s>n+3, the group 𝒟ωs​(M)subscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔𝑀\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega}(M) is H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} geodesically complete.

We note that when M𝑀M is two dimensional the symplectomorphism group and volume-preserving diffeomorphism group coincide so that our results strengthen those of Kouranbaeva and Oliver aswell as generalize them to the 2​n2𝑛2n-dimensional symplectic setting.

The symplectomorphism group equipped with the L2superscript𝐿2L^{2} metric on vector fields has already been conidered by Ebin [4] who showed that the corresponding geodesic equation is globally well-posed. In this setting the subgroup of Hamiltonian diffeomorphisms play a role in plasma dynamics analogous to the role played by the volume-preserving diffeomorphism group in hydrodynamics. In particular, the L2superscript𝐿2L^{2} geodesic equation is equivalent to the geodesic Vlasov equation (see Holm and Tronci [7] and the references therein) and we could consider the geodesic equation of the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric as the Lagrangian-averaged geodesic Vlasov equation.

Ebin [4] also asked if the L2superscript𝐿2L^{2} exponential map is a non-linear Fredholm map of index zero which was answered in the affirmative in [3]. Here we use the general framework of Misiolek and Preston [14] for studying exponential maps of right-invariant Sobolev Hrsuperscript𝐻𝑟H^{r} metrics and show

Theorem 1.2.

Let (M,ω)𝑀𝜔(M,\omega) be a closed, 2​n2𝑛2n-dimensional symplectic manifold with compatible Riemannian metric g𝑔g. Then, for s>n+3𝑠𝑛3s>n+3, the exponential map of the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric on 𝒟ωssubscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega} is a non-linear Fredholm map of index zero.

A bounded linear operator L𝐿L between Banach spaces is said to be Fredholm if it has finite dimensional kernel and cokernel. It then follows from the open mapping theorem that ran​Lran𝐿\text{ran}\,L is closed. L𝐿L is said to be semi-Fredholm if it has closed range and either its kernel or cokernel is of finite dimension. The index of L𝐿L is defined as ind​L=dimker⁡L−dimcoker​L.ind𝐿dimensionkernel𝐿dimensioncoker𝐿\mathrm{ind}\,L=\dim\ker L-\dim\mathrm{coker}\,L. The set of semi-Fredholm operators is an open subset in the space of all bounded linear operators and the index is a continuous function on this set into ℤ∪{±∞}ℤplus-or-minus\mathbb{Z}\cup\left\{\pm\infty\right\}, cf. Kato [9]. A C1superscript𝐶1C^{1} map f𝑓f between Banach manifolds is called Fredholm if its Fréchet derivative d​f​(p)𝑑𝑓𝑝df(p) is a Fredholm operator at each point p𝑝p in the domain of f𝑓f. If the domain is connected then the index of the derivative is by definition the index of f𝑓f, cf. Smale [18].

Let γ𝛾\gamma be a geodesic in a Riemannian Hilbert manifold. A point q=γ​(t)𝑞𝛾𝑡q=\gamma(t) is said to be conjugate to p=γ​(0)𝑝𝛾0p=\gamma(0) if the derivative D​expp⁡(t​γ˙​(0))𝐷subscript𝑝𝑡˙𝛾0D\exp_{p}(t\dot{\gamma}(0)) is not an isomorphism considered as a linear operator between the tangent spaces at p𝑝p and q𝑞q. It is called monoconjugate if D​expp⁡(t​γ˙​(0))𝐷subscript𝑝𝑡˙𝛾0D\exp_{p}(t\dot{\gamma}(0)) fails to be injective and epiconjugate if D​expp⁡(t​γ˙​(0))𝐷subscript𝑝𝑡˙𝛾0D\exp_{p}(t\dot{\gamma}(0)) fails to be surjective. In general exponential maps of infinite dimensional Riemannian manifolds are not Fredholm. For example, the antipodal points on the unit sphere in a Hilbert space with the induced metric are conjugate along any great circle and the differential of the corresponding exponential map has infinite dimensional kernel. An ellipsoid constructed by Grossman [6] provides another example as it contains a sequence of monoconjugate points along a geodesic arc converging to a limit point at which the derivative of the exponential map is injective but not surjective. Such pathological phenomena are ruled out by the Fredholm property because in this case monoconjugate and epiconjugate points must coincide, have finite multiplicities and cannot cluster along finite geodesic segments. In particular, the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} exponential map behaves like that of a finite dimensional manifold.

The paper is organized as follows: In the next section we give the functional analytic setting for the symplectomorphism group and the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric on vector fields. We then proceed to show that the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} exponential map is a local diffeomorphism on a neighbourhood of the identity diffeomorphism; that is, geodesics exist for at least a short time, are unique, and depend smoothly on their initial velocity. In the subsequent section we show that the domain of definition of the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} exponential map can be extended to the whole tangent space; this proves Theorem 1.1 above. In the second half of the paper we prove Theorem 1.2. Fredholm properties of Riemannian exponential maps on diffeomorphism groups is now well understood and a general theory has been laid out by Misiolek and Preston [14]. For this reason we will sketch the argument and indicate where the necessary changes occur. Finally, in section 6 we show that the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric carries conjugate points via some simple examples.

3. Geodesics of (𝒟ωs,⟨,⟩1)({\mathcal{D}}^{s}_{\omega},\langle,\rangle_{1})

We now proceed to form the Euler-Arnold equations on Te​𝒟ωssubscript𝑇𝑒subscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔T_{e}\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega}. In order to prove local existence and uniqueness it is convenient to rewrite the equations in terms of the flow equation (9). We will then show that the resulting second order (geodesic) equation is a smooth ODE on the infinite dimensional manifold 𝒟ωssubscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega} and can be solved using a standard Banach-Picard iteration scheme.

The basic technique was developed by Ebin and Marsden [5] in their study of the Cauchy problem for the Euler equations of hydrodynamics. The proof we use here is completely analogous to the proofs given in [5] and the proofs given by Shkoller [16] in his study of the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} metric on the volume preserving diffeomorphism group. Additionally, the basic theory for geodesics of right-invariant Sobolev metrics on certain diffeomorphism groups has been laid out by Misiolek and Preston [14]. For this reason we will give an outline of the argument and refer the reader to the aforementioned references.

Theorem 3.2.

Proposition 5.1.

Let M𝑀M be a compact, 2​n2𝑛2n dimensional, Riemannian manifold with compatible symplectic form ω𝜔\omega. Then, for s>n+3𝑠𝑛3s>n+3 and η∈𝒟ωs𝜂subscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔\eta\in\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega} the curvature tensor R¯η1subscriptsuperscript¯𝑅1𝜂\bar{R}^{1}_{\eta} is a bounded multilinear operator in the Hssuperscript𝐻𝑠H^{s} topology.

Proof.

Shkoller [16] gave an explicit formula for the H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} covariant derivative ∇1superscript∇1\nabla^{1} on the full diffeomorphism group 𝒟ssuperscript𝒟𝑠\mathcal{D}^{s}, see Theorem 3.1. The H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} covariant derivative on 𝒟ωssubscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega} is then given by ∇¯1=P∘∇1superscript¯∇1𝑃superscript∇1\bar{\nabla}^{1}=P\circ\nabla^{1}. To prove boundedness of the curvature tensor R¯1superscript¯𝑅1\bar{R}^{1} one first proves boundedness of the curvature tensor R1superscript𝑅1R^{1} on the full diffeomorphism group. The computations are tedious and do not differ in this situation so we refer the reader to [16] Lemma 4.1 through Proposition 4.1. To prove boundedness of the curvature tensor R¯1superscript¯𝑅1\bar{R}^{1} we use the Gauss-Codazzi equations which relates the curvature of the submanifold to that of the ambient manifold. To estimate the additional terms in the Gauss-Codazzi equations one proceeds just as in Theorem 4.1 [16], with the minor modification of applying the projection Pηsubscript𝑃𝜂P_{\eta} onto Tη​𝒟ωssubscript𝑇𝜂subscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔T_{\eta}\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega} and Qη=I−Pηsubscript𝑄𝜂𝐼subscript𝑃𝜂Q_{\eta}=I-P_{\eta}, which both depend smoothly on the basepoint η𝜂\eta (cf. [4]) and define pseudo-differential operators of class O​P​S1,00𝑂𝑃subscriptsuperscript𝑆010OPS^{0}_{1,0}. ∎

As a consequence, Jacobi fields exist, are unique, and globally defined along H1superscript𝐻1H^{1} geodesics in 𝒟ωssubscriptsuperscript𝒟𝑠𝜔\mathcal{D}^{s}_{\omega}.

Remark 5.3.

Note that the decomposition (19)-(22) must be applied with care. This is due to the loss of derivatives involved in calculating the differential of the left translation operator ξ⟶Lη​ξ⟶𝜉subscript𝐿𝜂𝜉\xi\longrightarrow L_{\eta}\xi and consequently of the adjoint operator in (4).
